\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Studies on market integration usually rely on time series data of price
 collected in selected markets.
 Starting from the law of one price, differences in the price of the product
 in different markets is then used to test hypotheses related to market
 efficiency.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The law of one price posits that adjustment of price margins between markets
 is a consequence of price arbitrage between the two markets, whereby traders
 buy the commodity in the low price market and sell the commodity in the
 high price market.
 If sufficient traders enter the business, increased demand for the commodity
 will drive up the price in the low price market while increase in supply
 will reduce the price in the thigh price market.
 In the long run, prices will return to a steady state long-run relationship
 that is determined buy the transaction cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One question that is less often address is how farm gate prices respond
 to changes in market centers.
 
