\begin_layout Section*
Prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, prices that farmers receive at the market are higher than the
 prices they can get when selling at the farm-gate.
 Even though no figures are given, this also the central stylized fact on
 which 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "fafchamps2005selling"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 build their analysis.
 This price difference is the result of transaction costs that are incurred
 by traders who need to collect, bulk and transport commodities sourced
 at the farm-gate to consumer centers, often many miles away.
 Transaction costs are difficult to measure, because they do not only include
 costs related to physical transport of the commodities, such as the cost
 of fuel or vehicle hire, but also more intangible costs such as search
 costs or a valuation of the risk taken by trader.
 Furthermore, it is often argued that traders collide to extract mark-ups
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "article"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bergquist2020competition"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find that that traders in Kenya act consistently with joint profit maximization
 and earn median markups of almost 40 percent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Surprisingly, in Malawi, we do not find significant differences in prices
 received at the farm-gate and prices received on the market (Table 
