\end_inset

 traders.
 The overall competitiveness of soy bean and maize markets is also reflected
 in the absence of any significant correlation between prices received at
 the farm gate and the number of traders that visited in the seven days
 leading up to the transaction.
 Alternatively, it may be that traders are able to get higher prices further
 up the value chain, partially offsetting the transaction cost they incur
 (for instance because of large quantities or because of a quality premium).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The way the data was collected also allows us to look at the dynamics of
 the price difference.
 It is well known that prices fluctuate substantially over time 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "RePEc:oup:jafrec:v:24:y:2015:i:2:p:230-253."
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We explore this by using the timestamp of the reported transactions to
 split the sample into 3 periods with approximately equal numbers of transaction
s.
 In the first period, running from April to May, prices are relatively high,
 and we see that the price farmers receive on the market is almost 7 percent
 higher.
 However, over time, when prices increase, that the premium disappears.
 Towards the end of the season, the difference between the price obtained
 on the market and at the farm-gate has virtually disappeared.
 This pattern does not seem to be related to competition: In fact, farmers
 report less traders contacting them in June and July than in April and
 May.
 Most likely, it is due to the fact that farmers are more likely to sell
 to the market early in the season when prices are high and more likely
 to sell to the market later in the season, when prices are lower.
\end_layout

